USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It's funny how Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, is trying to repeat the strategy of his predecessor, whom he thought was the dumbest, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally swallowed his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it over a copy machine from Bush's Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only does he use the wording "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he didn't even hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward".
He himself, three years ago, criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and disastrous in its consequences".
But the following months showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only one possible and so successful that today, Iraq is not even mentioned in the news.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but left his successor objectively in a much more grateful starting position than one might expect.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, most notably the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even criticized the hesitant snipers in the White House, despite his subordinate habits.
He asked for 40,000 men to turn the situation around.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general out of 10,000 troops.
He managed to squeeze another 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic part of Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish the process in three years.
Many doubt that the half-increase will produce the same results as the Iraq process.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honoring agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be trusted and no agreements are being respected.
The Afghan security forces are ill-prepared for these conditions, used to changing their masters every day as they see fit.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain a mere village of potatoes, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to thrive.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult given the ambiguity of the situation, which is further complicated by the Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the building of an "accessible state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, does not seem very realistic.
The timeline of Obama's strategy is striking in its voluntarism.
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse, and now it's on the verge of explosion.
To believe that the soldiers sent to the heat of war for the purpose of "coming home soon" will cause the miracle performed here can only be a soul truly romantic, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is a blatant irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see it as an indirect acknowledgement of American defeat.
The recent NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is on the decline.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindu Kush.
Another factor that could radically affect the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the intensified sanctions on Iran fail, the United States will face the overwhelming question of whether to try to resolve the problem by military force.
It will be answered just as Obama says America is moving to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any such solution would also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election, and therefore there is still plenty of time to come up with another strategy if this one turns out to be a total failure.
