Czech discovery: a substance that even deals with 'infected' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works against viruses that have already gained immunity to the drugs.
This fact is in some cases overridden by the fact that the compound for the common variant of the virus does not work as strongly as some of the drugs already available.
AIDS is not curable yet.
However, a combination of medicines that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body can significantly prolong the life of patients.
However, there are a number of side effects associated with their use.
In addition, incomplete suppression of the virus's reproduction results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to tackle resistance to the virus.
They showed that substances called metal carburanes act on a protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metal carbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that no other drug is currently used, and so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, scientists are coming up with new "enhanced" compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metal carbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms linked by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, the mature infectious virus particles would not be produced.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, explain scientists in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the researchers describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is then systematically modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The efficacy of this series of anti-HIV protease agents was tested in a laboratory and also against its resistant (resistant) variants derived from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metal carbores on the common enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for the resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modification make metal carbores interesting compounds for further research aimed at designing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
