The UN team has outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching unproven stance and mutual blame -- focused again on Friday on releasing a document that proposes ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years with the industrialized nations bearing the brunt of the burden in the short term.
The text, which may provide a basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminates the way forward.
But there was important progress in the negotiations, which were timed at the wrong time with over 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Created by an ad hoc UN task force, this text quietly states how much money rich countries should give to poor countries to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a whole range of options for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies so that they can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global warming should be that policymakers will still be able to tolerate.
This gives the process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior executive of the Sierra Club of Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, a 180-page condensation of the text of the negotiations to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement whereby industrial nations could jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by the year compared with 1990 levels, while the major developing countries could reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent during this period.
Together, countries could cut emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union negotiated swiftly on Friday a pledge to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries adopt climate change adaptation -- from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Still, Friday brought up the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated interviews last week.
US Special Envoy on Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected a speech calling for binding greenhouse gas emissions reductions for industrialized countries compared to voluntary in major emerging economies if they were not funded by the developed world.
The shift signalled that the Obama administration had taken a tougher line on China than Bush administration officials had just two years ago.
The United States will not join the treaty without the transfer of major developing countries and the implementation of actions, said Stern, who also complained that the text is not sufficient to ensure the restriction and should be checked by external observers.
Stern made the comment an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei told the US chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "rural sense" or "extreme irresponsibility" led to the announcement earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global warming.
With the future of the economic trajectory of the major world powers at stake, tensions have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrialized world and the emerging economies.
The current battle is mostly about saving economies rather than saving the planet, between China and the United States over their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world's most powerful countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take more drastic action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of limiting greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries became much more aggressive in finding ways to prevent large emitters from acting responsibly.
It's clearly a game about a new economic hegemony developing, said Ulate, who also serves as regional adviser on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for International Nature Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impacts of climate change have indicated that they would like to continue to push for a legally binding Copenhagen agreement, but the majority of the key participants said that the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, produced a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the small island nations' push "has given a political boost to the whole polyarctic process" in part because they are now united and demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The negotiations aroused new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the remaining contentious issues before the heads of government fight over an agreement.
High-ranking officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, got off the planes and walked through the Bell Center behind closed doors for meetings and new conferences so they could outline their demands for next week's review.
The sheer scale of the rally -- with 13,000 people commuting to and from the convention center every day, activists playing guitars staging ironic scenes at night about the countries they thought had sent them, and hand-to-hand proposals being passed on paper rather than e-mail -- was dominated by the challenge.
The intensity is only a build-up: Copenhagen was attended by almost all the key ministers and, earlier, by 60 heads of state.
We've gotten into the high-end, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, the deputy minister for global policy at the International Conservation.
We're getting heavy weights.
Britain 's first 140-mile-an-hour train defined this Monday 's feeling
At 5:13 Monday morning, the whistle blew through the sign of the train's departure, which marked the revolution in British transport.
The first high-speed passenger train in the country will reach 140 miles an hour, and will run from Ashford in Kent to St Pancras in London, covering a distance of 58 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister for Transport, then joined Mrs Kelly Holmes and boarded the first high-speed passenger train outside London.
He hopes the new service will eventually connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the large agglomerations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
Neglected standing water should reduce travel times on passenger and business routes, and the shift from airplanes and cars to railways could reduce carbon emissions and eliminate road congestion.
In theory, the three major political parties were all in favor of this vision.
But the tens of pounds needed to build a new national railway network, the inevitable project clashes and concerns about environmental damage have now held back the construction of Britain's high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to provide the government with a feasible study, delivered its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, the Times reported.
She provided him with a detailed map of the routes of the next planned phase of the high-speed network.
New routing connecting London to the West Midlands has been proposed within five metres in urban areas and neighbourhoods where environmental impact could be problematic.
In the open countryside, a 25-meter finish line was planned.
HS2 also envisages three options for the extensive high-speed network leading north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred option is a Y-shaped configuration where one high-speed line should lead to the West Midlands.
The line should split near Birmingham with one branch running from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and the other leading north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
One track should lead to Scotland.
"It seems that the most efficient choice has been made", said a railroad expert.
Once completed, the journey time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to two hours and 40 minutes.
The first stage, which will not open until 2025, could allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes compared to more than one hour at present.
The proposals should allow trains to run at 2,250 miles per hour, making the UK's network the fastest in Europe.
The initial line is already being designed to carry 400m long trains capable of carrying 1,100 people.
Up to 18 sets could be operated every hour on the London-Birmingham route.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet decided on the compatibility of the measure with the internal market.
In view of the capital constraints, it is envisaged that the existing station would be extended to cover the high-speed network.
Railway industry experts say only San Pancras International or Euston offer such potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he intends to implement the scheme, but extensive public consultation and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be made before the general election.
Even if it does set the wheels in motion, the network should be built in pieces.
Trains should first be put into service not on high-speed lines but on existing lines north of Birmingham and maintain travel times between London and Scotland of over three hours.
This is seen as the crucial junction point for ensuring the transition from airplanes to trains, the landmark for the railway revolution.
