The management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the big French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been futile...
For more than a decade, the management of large companies has been behaving in a way reminiscent of the way firms treated consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about making employees identify with "values" determined from above, as was the case in the past, when the products that came from the ideas of the chief factory technicians had to be forced on the consumer.
By making the customer the centre of business, the marketing revolution has set the strategy of market conquest in the right direction... even as authoritarian attempts to impose products different from the customer's preferences regularly return!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only a visible part of a much wider phenomenon affecting mainly the management.
This demobilization is adversely affecting the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires an active approach and foresight from all parties involved" and requires employees to make commitments that are completely at odds with the revenues of authoritarian management.
