The crib of the dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The seven-foot-long, six-foot-tall animal ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle-like claws, and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, it wouldn't be anything special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in Thursday's issue of the journal Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to display these physical features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangaea.
Tawa opens a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the kinship, distribution, and traits of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we find a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unheard of for Triassic fossils, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The find confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an unusual discovery: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only found in fragments".
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
The discovery is not particularly sensational, but it does confirm some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, however, so the attribution of pradinosaurs is mostly controversial.
For example, experts debate when lizards split into the three most important evolutionary lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyranosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and also the birds, the "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the herbivores Ornithischia (bird-eaters), which included Triceratops and Stegosaurus, for example.
Tawa Hallae is the original therapist, according to Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced characteristics, Nesbitt says.
For example, on the skull of the Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs that descendants of theropod birds also have.
Thanks to air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
At Tawa Hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
The Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Since the giant sauropod's related lineage later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation was probably already created by a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists inferred that lizards first appeared there.
Accordingly, three developmental lines soon split and spread from South America to all the continents that then formed a single land mass, like the supercontinent Pangaea.
And it would also be supported by the fact that the team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods along with Tawa Hallae.
The three cannot come from a common immigrant ancestor, scientists argue.
We believe that there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, one of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His conjecture may give a distorted picture, since there are many primitive dinosaur fossils left in South America, and they are rarely found on other continents.
How dinosaurs could prove that they evolved from a relatively rare sub-line of reptiles to the dominant vertebrates on Earth in the Middle Ages remains a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, including the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species evolved, while relatives went extinct and the Triassic and Jurassic intersected.
The story of success didn't last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, which the dinosaurs just happened to survive, but the reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could outrun the competition.
The story of success didn't last forever, anyway.
