Some people see images and hear voices that others cannot see or hear.
It's not just the mentally ill or the drug-addicted who blur the lines between fantasy and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we are allowed to surround ourselves with the wildest fantasies and fantasies.
But in the Western world today, people who experience waking dream states, seeing and hearing things that others cannot see or hear, are generally considered to be insane or drug addicts, or at least freaks.
But such images and voices are not limited to the mentally ill or the drug-addicted.
It's our imagination that's to blame: The same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paint pictures, or write novels, will here and there blur the lines between dream, imagination, and reality.
Dreams of altered states of consciousness can take many forms, at best we call them visions, at worst delusions.
Although the initiator and effect may vary, however, visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, drug experiences of New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanistic states of delusion, psychosis, and hallucinations can be traced to similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of neuronal transmitters in the brain - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is disturbed and the interactions between different parts of the brain are disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusions are very common in schizophrenic psychosis.
