The connection between delusion and sleep has been a concern of philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle understood hallucinations as a form of waking dream, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, noted in 1861 "a great similarity between delusion and dream states", and Sigmund Freud even described dreams as "psychosis, with all its nonsense, delusions, delusions of the senses".
