Ghosts are a terrible reality
About one percent of people will develop schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime, making it the second most commonly treated disorder in psychiatric clinics after depression.
In acute schizophrenia, people often can't distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, and they get into a state of wakefulness that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, delusions of belonging, or delusions of being haunted.
Especially common is hearing voices - voices that command, comment, or conduct dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon either.
The person is unable to distinguish between the important and the unimportant, the brain cannot filter out the distracting signals, the mind is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream opens up psychosis has built up a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the General Psychiatry Clinic of the University Clinic of Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he becomes passive, becoming, as in a dream, overwhelmed by events and unable to actively shape them.
Therefore, schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is mostly impossible, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is excluded.
To experience a hallucination for once in your life
Unlike in dreams, says Fuchss, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that one perceives in psychosis remains essentially preserved".
The delusions and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience occurs within the real framework.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why exactly our brains make these changes.
Exceptional circumstances can cause anyone to lose touch with reality in the short term, says Fuchs.
Not everyone develops into a psychotic state.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes aren't the only determining factor.
Scientists assume that people with disabilities have minimal brain damage.
We suspect that early in development there is damage to neuronal maturation in the brain, such as viral disease in the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains a mystery how the neurological system is affected, which has not been seen for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the trigger for psychosis, if it is available.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brains boil
The crazy thing is that psychotronic sufferers suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them, they swallow expensive medicines, others pay for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his findings in the book "Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf" (The Unreal World in Our Head).
Hallucinations are a typical symptom of psychosis, but they are also a surprisingly common symptom of many other disorders.
Besides mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, there are also often diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's, or brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of a healthy person hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Kastens, are made up of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They occur when the parts of the brain that process sensory perception are over-active or under-suppressed; when our brains are boiling or when we lack stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal from stimulation, stress, love worries, or other extraordinary conditions.
In more recent studies, up to a third of those interviewed reported experiencing hallucinations at least once in their lives.
