Since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she's not crazy.
Hallucinations are also the art of despair.
If someone is socially isolated or deprived of stimulation, he is more likely to have hallucinations, says Kasten.
I think the brain is not busy enough and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when, at 13, she learned that the man she had called her father for as long as she could remember was not her own father.
Because visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same areas of the brain that process real perceptions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality. "Every experience", says Kasten, "is in the brain, and reality is there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real".
Kasten also considers night dreams to be a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations in healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Compared to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The borderline between dream and hallucination
In our world of too much focus on consciousness, unfortunately, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic of Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a hard, painful disease, but it also brings positives, creativity -- delusion is also the art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has been studying what he calls the oneiroid form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness into a dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the subject perceives as real and cannot even distinguish them back from the waking state.
Oneiroid states of consciousness occur in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, such as patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
When a person is threatened with loss of the world and himself, such as permanent, complete immobility, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
Kind of a border state between dream and hallucination.
Because in reality, you can't handle a situation, you change the world, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intense form of sensory support and sensory transference in some unbearable situation that allows us humans our own ability to form, to pass into instant unconsciousness.
It's all real, even later in memory
Also, art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (Heart Exchange) as a salvation of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery and a heart transplant, his consciousness set off on a journey of several days, his body lying motionless in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he had created, visited foreign times and places: he became an old man chained to a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot guarding his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages amongst the nobility who make intoxicants out of blood.
He's on a motorcycle to his homeland, surfing in a hospital bed to a surf shop in the Alps, and he meets a Korean mobster.
He's completely immersed in the imaginary, everything is real, even later in his memories.
These inner paths are fundamentally different from any dream for Claussene.
A dream is a different state, describing your experience.
Unlike dreams, memories of these mental journeys are still vivid years later in trivial details.
Even more vivid and intense than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience shatters the horizon of our other authentic experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of the external reality are even in the waking state.
Any change in consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality".
A reality that can also be enriching.
