75% of working mothers have work-related problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, particularly among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and the working career of Spanish women' carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market because of motherhood.
The study highlights that there are many differences in opinion on the number of children at the beginning of cohabitation, depending on whether they are working or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job start living with their partner earlier, have their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, are putting off cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer children.
'Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years after the start of their life together with their partner.This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and have therefore had to postpone their life together and the arrival of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong influence on maternity, although it has a smaller influence on the time of initiation of cohabitation", explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of a child is their level of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, women with primary and secondary education gave birth to their first child at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education marry and have their first child before they find stable employment, while women with secondary or tertiary education go the other way and prefer to get a stable job before they marry and have their first child", says Delgado.
