The auxiliary system for the hand brake is already mandatory.
As with the ABS anti-lock system, the ESP stability control, the manual brake assist systems, will become mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, it is already a compulsory component of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others the deadline for the removal of the shortage is set, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase pedestrian protection, working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary braking system increases the emergency brake pressure, which is detected by the system after the driver steps on the brake.
But he can't always keep the pressure on until the end.
According to a study by car parts manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not brake before a collision, and half of them did not use the brake to their full potential.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this aid requires the maximum from the braking system, it shortens the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1 100 fatal pedestrian accidents could be avoided each year.
The reduction in this number will be even more marked - one in four accidents involving persons would be avoided, according to calculations - once so-called intelligent hand braking systems are introduced.
In this case, the vehicle shall be equipped with a system which detects (by radar or camera) obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even when the collision cannot be prevented, the device shall exert as much braking as possible and minimise the risk of damage.
